## Bean Scopes

| Scope | Lifecycle | Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| **singleton** (default) | One per ApplicationContext | Stateless services |
| **prototype** | New instance each request | Stateful/mutable objects |
| **request** | One per HTTP request | Web: request-scoped data |
| **session** | One per HTTP session | Web: user session data |
| **application** | One per ServletContext | Web: app-wide data |

```java
@Component
@Scope("prototype")  // new instance every time
public class ReportGenerator { ... }

// Or with web scopes
@Component
@RequestScope
public class RequestContext { ... }
```

### Injecting prototype into singleton — the problem!
```java
@Service // singleton
public class OrderService {
    @Autowired
    private ReportGenerator rg; // prototype — but injected ONCE at startup!
    // rg will always be the SAME instance — singleton wins!
}
```

## Injection Types

### Constructor Injection (preferred)
```java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    private final UserRepo userRepo;
    private final PaymentService paymentService;

    // @Autowired optional since Spring 4.3 (single constructor)
    public OrderService(UserRepo userRepo, PaymentService paymentService) {
        this.userRepo = userRepo;
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }
}
```
Advantages: immutable fields, visible dependencies, easy to unit test (just `new OrderService(mockRepo, mockPayment)`).

### Field Injection (avoid)
```java
@Autowired  // Spring injects via reflection — bypasses constructors
private UserRepo userRepo; // can't be final, hidden dependencies
```

## Circular Dependencies

If A → B → A (constructor injection), Spring throws `BeanCurrentlyInCreationException`.

Solutions:
1. **Redesign** — usually a sign of poor architecture
2. `@Lazy` on one of the injections — defers initialization
3. Use setter injection for one side

## BeanPostProcessor

`BeanPostProcessor` is the extension point Spring uses internally for AOP, `@Autowired`, `@Value`, `@PostConstruct` etc.

```java
@Component
public class LoggingBeanPostProcessor implements BeanPostProcessor {

    @Override
    public Object postProcessAfterInitialization(Object bean, String beanName) {
        // Called after every bean is initialized
        // Spring's AOP wraps beans in proxies HERE
        return bean; // or a proxy wrapping bean
    }
}
```
